During that period, the department leveled off in number, or did it continue to grow?
No.
Well, a whole lot of things happened.
Fall of 76, the Department of Horticultural Sciences split from this department.
I mean, it was taken from this department.
In the early 80s, the old Department of Plant Pathology and Physiology had broken up.
And then a Department of Plant Pathology and Microbiology was formed.
The geneticists in that department
went several directions, but we took some of them.
The plant physiologist went to several different departments, and we got some of those.
So we inherited faculty in the 80s.
I can't remember exactly what year that'd be in the late 80s, I guess.
It was certainly after Runge was here.
It had to be in the middle 80s.
So we lost a group in the mid-70s.
We were hiring at

fast enough pace then that probably, I'd say, faculty numbers just very momentarily low, decreased probably, and student numbers were, well, undergraduate student numbers peaked about 1977 in our department.
They dropped throughout the 80s.
They've been a very slow increase, but not more than 20% variation over quite a long time.
Graduate enrollment has been dropping now for about five or six years for a lot of reasons, I think.
It's been hard to maintain it in the university as a whole.
Funding, for one thing, international.

I don't think the Republican Congress has been particularly good for international development funds or funds that go into the international military that have a tendency to come back to us in the form of students.

so we lost we lost 19 international students between two fall semesters in numbers went from 70 to 51 international graduate students between two fall semesters i think it's 96 97 something like that and i think it's just a funding problem primarily that was a reduction in federal

Hard working.
